1. Business Understanding¶

Introduction to the Car Sales dataset¶

Craigslist is the one of the world's largest collection of used vehicles for sale, yet it's very difficult to collect all of them in the same place. Craigslist collects the used vehicles all over the world including Asia and Africa. It's hard to put all those used vehicles data together because huge data amount and some regional restriction such as currency float and privacy policy. This data only collected the used vehicles information in the United States where Craigslist shares the biggest market over the world. This data is scraped every few months, it contains most all relevant information that Craigslist provides on car sales including columns like price, condition, manufacturer, latitude/longitude, and 16 other categories.

The purpose of the dataset¶

Again, those used vehicles information was collected from Craigslist. They have all relevant information about the used cars they gave for sales including sales price. The Craigslist get those used cars information once they buy the car from previous owner or car reports or they just check the vin number of that used car they will have all the relevant information about that car. Since they have collected the information about the used car they bought, they will store that information into their database and put it online with the price for customers. Customer can access the information from anywhere instead of going to the retail store for price and information they need. Another reason they store those information besides for sales would be management level. Craigslist share the large proportion of the used cars market, managing those assets (aka used cars) effectively is also what they need to concern. With those used car information they stored, they can easily check those inventories.

Prediction task for your data¶

Through processing the data, we really want to know what are the key factors influence the sales price of the used cars on Craigslist. In short, our goal is giving the prediction of the price range of a car based certain attributes of the car information as accurate as possible.

Who else interested in the result?¶

Every potential used car consumer should be interesed on this model, since it could save you massive money once the prediction is accurate.

For internatioal students who newly enter U.S., they really want to buy an ideal car with desired price. They must interested on this analyise report.

How well would your prediction algorithm need to perform to be considered useful to these third parties?¶

The model should give a result of what impact factors of price are? and how they will influent the sell price? The price range of the prediction should be as accurate as possible.

Moreover, most international students have the consideration of the resalability of their cars, since they won't stay U.S. for a dacade. Therefore, we could give a prediction of resalability.

The reason why we delete those attributes:

Url: Link to the used car list on Craigslist. It makes no sense for analysis or prediction.

Vin: unique ID of each car. It makes no sense for analysis or prediction.

Lat & long: City coordinates in map. We have the city name which is the same and easier understanding in visualization.

Couny_name, county_fips: already have city and state information.

State_code: same as state name.

City: We dont need city name since we have satae

Weather: Weather is the temperature of the locat place in Nov. and Oct..

Make: We more care about Manfacturer than Make. Make is the model of the car under manfacturer.

Among the attributes with the missing value, we eliminate rows with missing value in those attributes because they have large number of missing values and it is hard to impute a value for them (Most of them are object, if we imputed a most frequent value, due to large number of missing values, it may influence the data quality and outcome). In other words, we believe imputation (only for those attributes) will impact on our data quality. Another reason we believe elimination is better that imputation is that we will still have large number of data after elimination. Our dataset will be good after elimination. (Only 'year' which with few missing values, it is OK to drop the rows with miss value)

#https://towardsdatascience.com/ways-to-detect-and-remove-the-outliers-404d16608dba
# We use IQR to define the outlier in dataset
Q1 = cars_imputed.quantile(0.25)
Q3 = cars_imputed.quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

noise_odometer = (cars_imputed.Odometer < (Q1.Odometer - 1.5 * IQR.Odometer)) | (cars_imputed.Odometer > (Q3.Odometer + 1.5 * IQR.Odometer))
noise_price = (cars_imputed.Price < (Q1.Price - 1.5 * IQR.Price)) | (cars_imputed.Price > (Q3.Price + 1.5 * IQR.Price))

cars_imputed = cars_imputed[~(noise_odometer | noise_price)]

Here we saw the price distribution in each condition. Condition from 1 to 6 represent salvage=1, fair=2, good=3, excellent=4, like new=5, new=6 Which is from worst to best. From box plot on the left, we can see the median price become higher with condition be better. From violin plot on the left, we can see the price distribution in each condition has skewness. In each condition, some high price value car exist. Thats maybe some luxury cars.

Some tricky points here. Likely new vehicles has higher median price than new ones. Thats interesting because we usually think new vehicles have highest average price. What we suggest here is to avoid choose Likely new vehicles. Another point is that Likely new vehicles and new vehicles price distribute evenly especially new vehicles. Likely new vehicles and new vehicles are good for customers who are not price sensitive.

4. Dimensionality Reduction¶

t-SNE is a nice tool to visualize and understand high-dimensional data. It is a dimensionality reduction methods which reduce dimensionality of data to 2 or 3 dimensions very like PCA. The main difference between these two methods is the way they put similarity together. The first step of t-SNE is to t- convert distances between data in the original space to probabilities. We compute conditional probabilities which will be used to generate joint probabilities. It then pick object with similar high probability and then it together.

In [150]:
import sklearn
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA #Though we did not use
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE

#select the subset I want
df_Y = cars_imputed.Price
df_X = cars_imputed[['Odometer','Year','Condition','Cylinders','Size']]
#Price is the target 

#implement t-sne
X_tsne = TSNE(learning_rate=300,n_components=2).fit_transform(df_X)

#we set higher learning_rate than ususal due to huge dataset

We set Price as potential target. This is what we want to predict and analyses in this project. We set the learning rate a little bit higher than usual because the huge dataset we have.
